THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"seg.hyperscale","op":"set","value":0.28,"note":"CE hyperscale-owned share far below global 0.44; self-build concentrated outside CE-7"},{"nodeId":"seg.colocation","op":"set","value":0.32,"note":"Mix-shift: the displaced weight lands in colocation, per CBRE's European ordering"}], likelihood 0.58, category model-structure

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "CE hyperscale 0.44 is a global-split mirage: Europe's self-build sits in Ireland/Sweden/Belgium, and Frankfurt is colocation",
 "narrative": "The segment axis applies Synergy's GLOBAL capacity split (48% hyperscale × 0.91) to a geography axis built entirely on Central European colocation MW. But CBRE's Europe-specific data says ~60% of operational hyperscaler self-build capacity sits in Ireland, the Netherlands, Sweden and Belgium — three of the four outside CE-7 — and that European colocation 'will remain significantly larger' than hyperscale self-build. Inside CE, hyperscalers show up mostly as TENANTS in Frankfurt and Amsterdam colo halls, where the fit-out and PDU procurement decision often sits with the colo operator or a global tenant framework, not a CE buyer. The model's biggest cell — DE × hyperscale — is therefore substantially phantom, and the true CE mix is inverted toward colocation buyers with different procurement paths.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "CBRE Q4-2025: ~60% of Europe's operational hyperscaler self-build capacity is located in Ireland, Netherlands, Sweden, Belgium; and colocation in Europe 'will remain significantly larger' than hyperscaler self-build — the opposite ordering from the model's 0.44 vs 0.18",
   "refs": [
    "digest:seg-mix#c16",
    "digest:seg-mix#c15"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The 0.44 was produced by rescaling a raw GLOBAL Synergy share; no Europe- or CE-scoped hyperscale share has ever been observed, and the 'cross-check' (Q1-2025 44% global) is a different quantity that coincidentally matches. Hyperscale demand in CE flows through colo halls whose take-up already outstrips supply",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.hyperscale",
    "digest:seg-mix#c6",
    "digest:seg-mix#c24"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The DE(0.50) × hyperscale(0.44) cell — the largest cell in the cube and the implied beachhead for selling to large operators — is largely phantom in CE; weight belongs in colocation, whose buyer, spec and procurement cadence differ from what the venture is building for",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:geo.DE",
    "ledger:seg.colocation",
    "profile:Who is the primary buyer you'll sell through first?"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "seg.hyperscale carries maturity 'triangulated' with multiple Synergy vintages agreeing on trajectory — it looks like the best-sourced segment node. The agreement is real but among GLOBAL figures; nothing in the ledger flags that the quantity was never observed at European scope, and Frankfurt's AI headlines make 'hyperscale dominates CE' feel confirmed daily.",
 "falsifier": "A Europe- or CE-scoped capacity split (CBRE, Synergy regional cut, or EUDCA country tables) showing hyperscale-owned capacity at ≥40% of CE-7 total data-center capacity.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "CBRE's Europe-specific reporting directly contradicts the global ordering, and the cross-corpus tension flags that no CE-scoped hyperscale share exists; the open question is only magnitude, not direction. [evidence revision: The specific CBRE Q4-2025 figure (60% of self-build in IE/NL/SE/BE and colocation ~50% larger than self-build) is now directly confirmed by an independent secondary source, strengthening both load-bearing premises about geographic mislocation and colo-vs-hyperscale ordering. However, no source directly quantified the CE-7 hyperscale-owned share, so the magnitude of the 'phantom' DE×hyperscale cell remains inferential — a modest upward revision is warranted, not a large one.]"
}

